snippet.title: Paris 3rd Arrondissement - 20 in 20 Day 3 -  The Haut Marais, Paris
snippet.description:
Paris' 3rd Arrondissement is often referred to as the Haut Marais (or upper Marais) and is loaded with delicious food. Get all of my recommendations in my guide http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide and be sure to check out the game before you come http://travelunlock.com - Fringe coffeeshop, for example, is a Waypoint in the game.

Help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:

Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide for tons of recommendations in the 3rd Arrondissement of Paris and lots, lots more.

More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by: Joakim Karud

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay:
Thanks for the live stream last night. I hope you were able to meet up with your friends afterwards; it's always good to be around friends after something like that happens. It's hard seeing how people are affected as events unfold but it does show how much buildings really resonate with people on a deep emotional level. As avantguache said, Notre Dame will rise again as York Minster did.
Really enjoying 20 in 20. Feels like I'm getting to know Paris all over again! Picasso Museum is on the list for the next visit. Can't wait till you get to the 8th for Musée Nissim de Camondo. Went last year and I want to live inside it!
A wee request, if you wheel through interesting streets, I'd love to see more of the shop fronts. I love the electrical shop you go to; the window display is so eye-catching. Is it just me who likes to nose in shop windows??? Anyhoo, lovely to see all the flowers blooming in the park.

comments.textDisplay: On my first trip to Paris in 2012, the Picasso museum was closed for renos. :( My second trip in 2014, the grand re-opening happened the Sunday after I left. Finally go there in 2017 for a wonderful exhibit put on by Picasso's son, Paulo, of his mother's treasures. Picasso's personal collection of his friend's paintings on the 3rd floor are priceless. I also did not know that he worked with other mediums such as leather and cloth.

comments.textDisplay: Jay, explain the difference between quartier and arrondissement.
comments.textOriginal: Jay, explain the difference between quartier and arrondissement.

replies.textDisplay: A quartier is a neighborhood and that can be defined by any number of things (cultural or landmarks etc) and might span more than one arrondissement or an arrondissement may have many quartiers.  The arrondissement is more of an administrative line in the sand. . .a district . . each one has it's own mayor.

comments.textDisplay: The Carnavalet is one of the best "deals" we've found.  You "donate" as you walk in (Don't be cheap fellow cheapskates)  and it offers a very broad selection of art and historical artifacts, from commercial signage to fine art.  In the basement you go back in time to archeological exhibits.  (Neanderthal space invader?)  It's not on the typical tourist agenda.  I think it is a place that people living in Paris take their children to inspire an interest in Parisian history.

comments.textDisplay: Gustave!  And his papa- he sure loves you and the wheel.  So good to wheel around the Haut Marais with you.  I didn't know if you'd get anything up after the hours being present for the Notre Dame fire.  I am diving into it's history- Selma Hyack's (sp?) husband donated 100 MILLION dollars towards the fund being collected for it's repair/renovation/renewal!  Before the fire Paris had estimated the cost of renovation at 180 million, so this donation was amazing.  Everything about Notre Dame is inspiring to me.  I love learning so much about Paris, and I love seeing familiar places as I get to know the city with you zooming around! (Oh the food!!!)...

comments.textDisplay:
As weird as it might sound, there is really a very nice inspiring energy around such a tragedy yesterday ... I heard there was a human chain who saved most of the relics yesterday during the fire, and already from France alone there are hundreds of million pledged to rebuild Notre Dame. This happened before with Reims and it was rebuilt successfully too with the incredible human unity who came together for this. The whole world was watching ..., and the importance of this building as a crucial part of human history is unquestionable.
Cheers Jay! Thanks again for bringing us together yesterday live. Enjoy Paris! 🌷🌷🌳🌷

comments.textDisplay: Thank you for live streaming last night your stream was how I found and I don't think I would have got a sense of how much it affected Parisians without watching it. My heart is breaking for Paris and its people who have suffered another painful tragedy. Thank god no one was killed or badly hurt.  Notre Dame will rise again just like York minster did after it was almost destroyed by similar although smaller fire in 1984. it's now almost exactly like it was before even its beautiful rose window which was badly damaged was restored I hope you and your fellow Parisian can take heart from that.

comments.textDisplay: It’s hard to comment on this one, knowing what came later... I have some good memories of the Marais and the 3rd— I actually did go to the Carnavalet several times and it is indeed really good for French history! Hopefully it’ll re-open soon. The Picasso Museum was closed all four years I was there, and opened shortly after I left. Bummer. I got to see the Picasso Museum in Antibes, though, so it balanced out. Thank you, as others have said, for the livestream. I appreciated it, too. 🙏🏼
